# TypeScript/JavaScript Rules

## Type Safety

- Prefer `strict: true` in tsconfig.json
- Avoid `any` - use `unknown` and narrow with type guards
- Use explicit return types for public functions
- Prefer interfaces for object shapes, types for unions/intersections

```typescript
// Good
function processUser(user: User): ProcessedUser {
  return { ...user, processed: true };
}

// Avoid
function processUser(user: any): any {
  return { ...user, processed: true };
}
```

## Modern Syntax

- Use ES modules (`import`/`export`) over CommonJS
- Prefer `const` over `let`, never use `var`
- Use optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`)
- Use template literals over string concatenation

## Async Patterns

- Prefer `async/await` over `.then()` chains
- Always handle errors with try/catch or `.catch()`
- Use `Promise.all()` for parallel operations

```typescript
// Good
const [users, posts] = await Promise.all([
  fetchUsers(),
  fetchPosts()
]);

// Avoid
const users = await fetchUsers();
const posts = await fetchPosts();
```

## Error Handling

- Create custom error classes for domain errors
- Include context in error messages
- Never swallow errors silently

```typescript
class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(public field: string, message: string) {
    super(`${field}: ${message}`);
    this.name = 'ValidationError';
  }
}
```

## React (TSX/JSX)

- Use functional components with hooks
- Prefer named exports for components
- Use `React.FC` sparingly (prefer explicit props)
- Memoize expensive computations with `useMemo`/`useCallback`

```typescript
// Good
interface ButtonProps {
  onClick: () => void;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

export function Button({ onClick, children }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button onClick={onClick}>{children}</button>;
}
```

## Imports

- Group imports: external, internal, relative, types
- Use path aliases when configured (`@/components`)
- Avoid circular dependencies

## Testing

- Use descriptive test names
- Follow AAA pattern: Arrange, Act, Assert
- Mock external dependencies, not internal modules
- Prefer integration tests for complex logic

## Dependencies

- Keep dependencies minimal
- Prefer well-maintained packages with types
- Pin versions in production (`package-lock.json`)
- Audit regularly (`npm audit`)

## Performance

- Use `React.lazy()` for code splitting
- Avoid inline object/array literals in JSX props
- Use `key` props correctly in lists
- Profile before optimizing
